0.body: The following chapters contain documentation on the game engine project I am working on, which can be found here . It also serves some other purposes, such as a reference point for me to see how I have improved and changed since this was made, as well as a sort of instructions book for myself and and others who find it useful. The Core section goes over lessons learned from making the lower level core library (before working on the rest of the engine), extending functionality of the language to make things easier (for example, adding portable coroutines). The API section is an API reference for the whole engine (including some core components), mostly serving as documentation, with some implementation details where necessary.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: I have chosen to move all of the utilities that wrap around the C++ and SFML interface into Core, keeping the foundations separate from the rest of the engine. The following chapters are much more in-depth than the API reference, and explain the concept behind each method, why it is useful for the engine, some implementation details and other sources if required. Some parts of Core are already documented in the API reference (e.g. Durations ), and some future parts will be too, as they are much simpler, and don't require learning new concepts to create.

3.body: Everyone's favourite topic to argue about, memory management. This page will go over the custom memory allocators the engine uses, why, and most importantly, what they do. First of all, why? The standard library implementation for allocating heap memory is to use malloc or new to allocate memory, and free or delete to deallocate memory. These functions are designed to have few constraints, which can lead to problems such as memory leaks, double frees, segmentation violation, and a mess of object lifetime management. We can't just replace these implementations, as they do have their uses (and are even used in the solution to access the heap), but we can provide alternatives that can help during certain situations. The engine's implementation uses new to allocate a large array of bytes, and then allocates objects into that array, allowing better control over memory, and even object lifetimes, allowing the user to deallocate multiple arbitrary objects at once, and without worrying about memory leaks, as all of the objects allocated have the same maximum lifetime as the array. Below are some sources, which explain each allocator as well as provide basic implementation details: Memory Allocation Strategies - Part 1 Memory Allocation Strategies - Part 2 Memory Allocation Strategies - Part 3 Untangling Lifetimes: The Arena Allocator With that said, let's look at the allocators.

4.body: Also known as a linear allocator, the arena allocator is very simple in concept. You have a large array of bytes available, and an offset within the array. To allocate an object, you return the array pointer plus the offset, and increase the offset by the size of the object. You cannot free individual items, but instead you clear the whole arena at once. Due to the way that computers read memory, the engine's implementation of arena allocation gains performance at the cost of space. Computers read multiple bytes of memory at once, but can only do it at regular intervals. This is known as n-byte alignment , and allows the CPU to read memory faster. This means that we must pad each allocation to make sure it has the correct alignment - for example, if we allocate a single byte, we must pad the next allocation to align it. In reality, memory arenas become slightly more complex when object-oriented programming is introduced. This is why the engine exposes two arena allocators: arena - uses extra memory to store type information for each allocation, allowing constructors and destructors to be called when required. fast_arena - a more barebones approach that does not call destructors, so is more appropriate for primitives, or C-style programming. Both allocators expose the same functions, which are listed below: arena(const size_t size) / fast_arena(const size_t size) - constructs the arena, allocating an internal buffer of size bytes T* allocate() - allocates an object of type T, in arena a struct containing type information is pushed to a seperate stack T* allocate(const size_t aligh) - allocates an object of type T with a custom alignment, in arena a struct containing type information is pushed to a seperate stack void clear() - clears the memory arena, in fast_arena, this simply resets the offset, in arena, it pops each element from the seconds stack and uses the type information to call destructors correctly

4.title: The Arena Allocator

5.body: A stack allocator is very similar to an arena allocator, with a few key differences that change its use. When a new element is pushed, a header is added to the storage that provides enough information so that you can pop items off of the stack, rather than only being able to clear it. This has a very slight size and speed overhead, but can be much more useful when used correctly. Below are the member functions of the stack allocator: stack(const size_t size) - constructs the stack, allocating an internal buffer of size bytes T* allocate() - allocates an object of type T T* allocate(const size_t align) - allocates an object of type T with custom alignment void free(T* t) - frees an object and calls its destructor. This deallocates anything above this object, but does not call the destructors, as it is intended to be used similarly to a pop operation void clear() - clears the stack, this does not call destructors as type information is not available
5.breadcrumbs: Core » Memory Management » The Stack Allocator
5.title: The Stack Allocator

6.body: The two above entries describe allocators that allow the user to allocate arbitrarily-sized objects, but only support linear allocation. The pool allocator only allows allocations of the same size, but can support deallocating any object in the pool. This is achieved by first using the arena allocator. When an object is deallocated, it's pointer is pushed to a linked list of free'd objects. When allocating, the list is checked first, and the pointer can be removed from the list and reinitialised, but if the list is empty, it uses the arena allocator. Below are the member functions of the pool allocator: pool(const size_t size) - constructs the pool, and calls the constructor of the memory arena, passing size as the argument T* allocate(const size_t align = DEFAULT_ALIGNMENT) - allocates a new object, calling its constructor, will use the default alignment if one is not provided void free(T* t) - deallocates an object, calling its destructor and places it on the free'd list void clear() - clears the buffer, does not call any destructors
